{"add":{"doc":{"id":"8b014add6f4fdd749b330365761858863a0ce2f25e8982bbed0510f46bea3c48","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/07/RhoticEngland2.png/200px-RhoticEngland2.png","previous":[],"after":["The earliest traces of a loss of /r/ in English appear in the early 15th century and occur before coronal consonants, especially /s/, giving modern \"ass (buttocks)\" (Old English ears, Middle English ers or ars), and \"bass (fish)\" (OE b√¶rs, ME bars).[1] The main phase of /r/-loss began during the 15th century, and was characterized by sporadic and lexically variable deletion, such as monyng \"morning\" and cadenall \"cardinal\".[1] These /r/-less spellings appear throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, but are uncommon and are restricted to private documents, especially ones written by women.[1] No English authorities describe loss of /r/ in the standard language prior to the mid-18th century, and many do not fully accept it until the 1790s.[1]"]}}}